The paper deals with the inapproximability of finding Nash equilibrium in various game-theoretic settings, which is a central topic in computational game theory (cs.GT). The PPAD-completeness result is a well-known result in complexity theory (cs.CC). The paper also uses techniques from computational complexity and graph theory (cs.DS) to prove the inapproximability results. The paper also discusses the inapproximability of Bayesian Nash equilibrium, which is a topic in artificial intelligence (cs.AI). Finally, the paper discusses the inapproximability of market equilibrium, which is a topic in economics and computational economics (cs.EC).
